  "why": "The paper describes mutations that add Gaussian or random noise to pixel values (fine-grained, in-memory perturbations) and a shift operation that reorders pixels, but it does not describe any steps to enforce input-format constraints (such as clipping mutated pixel values to the integer [0,255] range or rounding to discrete greyscale indices) nor does it discuss whether mutated inputs are serialized or whether failures survive serialization. Because the HDC encoding explicitly uses a discrete value HV memory indexed by greyscale values, applying floating-point perturbations without documented clipping/rounding can produce in-memory perturbations that would be altered or lost when converting back to standard serialized image formats. The paper therefore does not demonstrate that generated failures are preserved under serialization and does not enforce the relevant input-format constraints, so it meets the metric definition for Low.",
  "evidence": "Page 3, Section III.A (Encoding): \"For the MNIST dataset we use in this paper, since the image size is 28×28 and the pixel range is 0 to 255 in greyscale, we flat a single image into an array with 784 elements with values ranging from 0 to 255.\"; \"The value HV memory accommodates 255 HVs, each representing a pixel’s greyscale value.\" Page 4, Section IV (HDTest Framework) and Table I (Mutation strategies): \"The first two strategies, gauss and rand add Gaussian and random noise onto the image, resulting in holographic mutation on the image.\"; Table I entries: \"rand apply random noise over the entire image\" and \"gauss apply gaussian noise over the entire image.\" Page 4, Section IV (HDTest Framework): \"To ensure the added perturbations are within an 'invisible' range, we set a threshold for the distance metric during fuzzing (e.g., L2 < 1).\" -- Nowhere in the mutation description, encoding, or experimental evaluation does the paper state any clipping, rounding, integer re-quantization, or handling of serialization to enforce the [0,255] integer pixel constraints or demonstrate that adversarial inputs persist after saving/serialization."
